dataIdInfo.idPurp: GPS data collection of prairie dog activitiy on OSMP land that originates in 1996. These data was updated in 2012 to include an "Activity" subtype of either Inactive (1) if there is no record of the colony after it is once active, or Active (2) if the colony is globally positioned by a Wildlife Ecologist. Prairie Dog Identifiers are PD_ID and make up 155 colonies as of 2013 fall data collection.
dataIdInfo.idAbs: GPS data collection of prairie dog activitiy on OSMP land that originates in 1996.These data was updated in 2012 to include an "Activity" subtype of either Inactive (1) if there is no record of the colony after it is once active, or Active (2) if the colony is globally positioned by a Wildlife Ecologist. Prairie Dog Identifiers are PD_ID and make up 155 colonies as of 2013 fall data collection. The Year attribute is the year of prairie dog data collection. The Year Acquired attribute is the year that OSMP acquiried the primary property inwhich the prairie dogs exist. Prairie dog data collection is in 1-5 ft spatial resolution. OSMP Prairie Dog Colonies feature class is updated annually and is posted for online download on osmp.gov.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Open Space and Mountain Parks Wildlife Ecologists GIS staff
dataIdInfo.suppInfo: The null values are a text string and do not constitute spatial query. The null values serve as placeholders for the prairie dog colonies that were unmonitored prior to OSMP land acquisition. Every PD_ID has a record from 1996, null if it is prior to OSMP possession, and then monitored and determined active or inactive. The inactive polygons are generated by "no data" holes in the annual collection. Since Wildlife Ecologists only tracked active colonies, if one became inactive, there is no data collected. The inactive polygons inherit the spatial characteristics of the most recent active polygon and is classified as "Inactive". The active polygons are generated by the Wildlife Ecologists GPSing through ground truth analysis of active prairie dog colonies on OSMP land.
